%%
%% RECUEIL / de Chants et Danses Populaires / EDITE PAR / "LA BOURRE"
%%  Socit Artistique / des Originaires du Massif Central
%%  actuellement migrs dans l'agglomration parisienne
%%  SIGE SOCIAL: / 13, Bd BEAUMARCHAIS / PARIS - (IVe) / 4e EDITION
%%  Musique revue et mise au point / par J CANTELOUBE
%%
%% Published 1929
%%
%% Page photographs published online by Gary Chapin at http://accordeonaire.blogspot.co.uk 
%% Abc notation tune transcriptions by and (C) Steve Mansfield, http://www.lesession.co.uk,
%%  under the Creative Commons license as detailed at http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/
%%
%% Specifically :-
%%  Please preserve the Z: fields in any and all downstream usage of these abc transcriptions.
%%  If redistributing the entire file please preserve this entire header intact and unaltered.
%%  You are free to amend, alter and redistribute the abc notation of individual tunes, 
%%   but any and all changes should be documented through appropriate additional N: and Z: fields 
%%   (whilst preserving the existing N: and Z: fields) before any redistribution.
%%
%%
%% Editorial notes : 
%% -----------------
%% I welcome notification of any transcription errors (e.g. actual erroneous divergences from the 
%%  sheet music on the scanned page) via the contact details on http://www.lesession.co.uk 
%%
%% This is a reproduction of the music as published in the 1929 book. Note spacing is as in the source.
%%
%% Canteloube's dynamic markings, performance notes etc. have been reproduced as follows: 
%%  Dance/tune forms (Bourre etc.) have been transcribed as R: fields, 
%%   initial textual expression and tempo indicators (Assez anim etc.) as N: fields.
%% Crescendos, diminuendos, fermata etc. have been reproduced.
%% In addition Canteloube added various other text notations which have been transcribed as text comments 
%%  at the appropriate point. Nit-pickers may therefore possibly find what could be regarded as 
%%  minor inconsistencies in my choices between N: fields, !! fields, and text; enjoy.
%%   
%% Tunes 55 to 59 form a linked suite entitled 'Rveillez' - I have represented this 
%%  through separate tunes with secondary editorial title fields. Another transcriber might have decided to 
%%  represent this as a single piece with multiple P: sections. 
%%
%% This is a LeSession production from the Massif Central corner of the High Peak of Derbyshire, England.
%%  April-June 2012. Made in EasyAbc and Textpad, and verified against abcm2ps 6.3.3. using an English concertina, 
%%  other abc renderers and instruments may vary.
%%
%% Abc tutorial available at http://www.lesession.co.uk/abc
%%
%% La Bourree.abc - file v1.0
%% 
<end>

L:1/8

Z:Steve Mansfield www.lesession.co.uk April 2012
K:G
|: A B G | (FD) G A2c | B2 B A B G | (FD) G A2 B |
A3 A B G | (FD) G A2c | B2 G A c G | (FD) G A2 B |
!fermata! G3 | G z !fine!B/c/ ||[M:2/4][L:1/16] "Ritournelle Violon, Vielle ou Cabrette" d2Bc d2Bc | defe d2Bc | defe d2Bc |
d4 BGBd | c2A2 BAGA | B2G2 G2Bc | d2Bc d2Bc |
defe d2Bc | defe d2Bc | !fermata!d4 BGBd | c2A2 BAGA | !fermata!G4!D.C.!:|
<end>

L:1/8
N:Assez anim
N:La Bourre 4th edition 1929, page 16
C:J. Canteloube
Z:Steve Mansfield www.lesession.co.uk April 2012
K:G
!f!D2 "refr."|:B > A G3A B > c | (B>A) G3G c > B |
A6D2 | B > A G3A B e | (d3 c/B/) A4 |
G2 A > B G4 | A2 B > c A2 D2 | B2 A > B G G A > B |
c4 !crescendo(!B2 c d | e3!crescendo)! e f2 e2 | d4!diminuendo(! G2 c!diminuendo)! B | A8 |
!fermata! G6 !fine!|| G > G "couplet" | [K:C] c4 G G A > d | c4 G2 z F |
E E F G G3 G | A A G F A4 | B2 B B A G A B |
c2 e2 d3 c | B4 !fermata! A2 D > D | A3 c B2 A G |
A4 c2 B A | G E !crescendo(!F G A B c > d!crescendo)! | (ed/c/) !diminuendo(!B4 A!diminuendo)! > A |
d3c A2 G > A | c4 A2 !crescendo(!B > c!crescendo)! |d4 !fermata! d2 D2 !D.C.! :|
<end>

% woodenflute.abc
%
% The woodenflute mailing list exists to discuss all aspects of the wooden flute -
% music, history, technique, players, making, workshops, festivals, new CDs, and gossip.
%
% In the course of discussions, tunes were often posted to the list in abc format.
% These tunes were posted to illustrate a point, to answer a query, or just as one
% wooden flute player sharing a good tune with the members of the list.
%
% The file woodenflute.abc comprises the 641 abc tunes posted to the list between
% October 1998 and April 2003. I have made an honest attempt to credit all individual abc notations
% to the correct transcriber, and to observe any copyright issues relating to tunes
% in the file : I will happily correct any errors. The archive stops at April 2003 because, for no 
% very good reason I can discern, the users just stopped posting tunes to the list.
%
% I have manually tidied abc notation where necessary to generate a readable abc file, but without
% (intentionally) altering the actual transcription except in correcting certain glaringly 
% obvious errors or ommissions. The abc has been tested and found OK against my copies of 
% abcm2ps and Abc2Win, your mileage may vary. See my abc tutorial at http://www.lesession.co.uk.
%
% Multiple versions of the same tune may sometimes be found in the woodenflute archives - 
% this is a feature not a bug, although exactly the same transcription should not appear twice. 
% There is not one correct version of a traditional tune (or indeed of many newly-composed tunes), 
% and different transcriptions show either regional variations, players' styles, 
% or just the effect of the aural tradition in action.
%
% This file was downloaded from http://www.lesession.co.uk . 
%
% This file now comprises all of the tunes
% previously online in woodenflute.abc, wf_update1.abc, wf_update2.abc, and wf_update3.abc 
% (the original update files are also still available for any old hyperlinks). This is purely 
% because we have moved on from the download speeds offered by the 56K modems 
% prevalent when this tune collection was originally created.
%
% Details of how to join the woodenflute mailing list (of which I am a member,
% but not the owner) may be found at www.woodenflute.com.
<end>

<start>
X: 76
T:Johnny McGoohan's
M:2/2
L:1/8
C:Ed Reavy
S:The Collected Compositions of Ed Reavy
R:Reel
N:Good musicians need good listeners, and two
N:of the best listeners where Johnny and his wife Katey. Johnny would
N:be waiting on his front porch hours before "the fellows" were
N:expected on an evening for a session of music; and no matter how
N:long they played, it was never too late for a few more tunes at
N:the McGoohans. Tea and skohn did not mean (as it usually does) that
N:the fiddling would stop. As Johnny would put it, "We'll have a bite
N:to eat and be back at it for a few more before the night is done."
N:And Katey would never disagree.
Z:Joseph Reavy

N:The concluding line of O'Driscoll's refrain in Yeats' poem, "The Host
N:of
N:he air".
N:O'Driscoll dreamed that his wife Bridget was taken by the Host as he
N:was
N:laying harmlessly at
N:cards with "the merry old men." When O'Driscoll awoke from his dream,
N:all that remained of the dream was the strange unearthly sound of a
N:pipe
N:piping away in the distant air- "And never was piping so sad, And
N:never was piping so gay."

X: 113
T:Nonesuch
M:C|
L:1/8
Q:120
N:Almost the same as "A la Mode de France"
H:Nonesuch was built in 1538 by Henry VIII over the demolished property
H:of the village of Cuddington, near Epsom Wells in Sussex, to be the
H:most ostentatious hunting lodge ever made.  At the very end of her
H:life, Elizabeth I visited Nonesuch, as a guest of Lord Lumley,
H:son-in-law of the Earl of Arundel, and it was reported that "there is
H:much dancing of country dances in the privy chamber at Nonesuch,
H:the Queen's majesty, who is exceedingly pleased therewith".

X: 167
T:The Blessings of Silver
M:2/2
L:1/8
C:Ed Reavy
S:The Collected Compositions of Ed Reavy
R:Reel
N:Written for Lou and Mary Quinn's
N:twenty-fifth wedding anniversary. Ed loved the connotations of
N:the title: the blessings of twenty-five years of marriage, the
N:blessings of a couple growing old together, and the many rewards
N:of family life. Ed admired Lou not only because of his musical
N:talent, but also because he was a self-made man who set high standards
N:
N:for other immigrants who followed him to the New World.

<start>
X: 168
T:The Bog of Allen
M:2/2
L:1/8
C:Ed Reavy
S:The Collected Compostions of Ed Reavy
R:Reel
N:Mentioned eloquently in Joyce's short story,
N:"The Dead" (in Dubliners). This desolate region reminds us of Yeats'
N:line "the drifting, indefinite bitterness of life" Ed has always felt
N:that far too much is made of Ireland's greenery and not enough said
N:of her terrible greyness. Ed has lived to see the whole of Ireland,
N:and he has tried to get as much of it as he could into his own tunes.
Z:Joseph Reavy

X: 273
T:Llef Harlech [Harlech's cry]
R:?
C:trad, second part variation by Antwn Owen Hicks
D:Carreg Lafar 'Hyn', Sain SCD 2205
H:&gt;    From: Keith Davies Jones &lt;kjones@cc.umanitoba.ca&gt;
H:&gt; This tune was noted down sometime in the late eighteenth century by a
H:&gt; German violinist, Johann Baptist Malchair, who heard it sung 'in the
H:&gt; vicinity of Harlech Castle'. In 1807, Dr William Crotch, professor of
H:sic
H:&gt; at Oxford University,  published it in a compilation of lectures entit
H:d
H:&gt; 'Specimens of Various Styles of Music'. In 1963, Sir Thomas and Lady
H:&gt; Parry-Williams wrote the words 'Beth yw'r haf i mi?',  and the song
H:&gt; came home again to Wales.
H:&gt; (Huw Williams, 'Canu'r Bobol',  1978)
Z:Lesl
M:C|
K:Edor
|:eBBA B2AG|FGAB GFE2|EBBA B2AG|FGAF E4:|

X: 436
T:Fil, fil a rn 
R:air
H:a very popular Donegal song "Fil, Fil A Run O\", written in 1739. It
H:is the lament of a mother whose son "changed his coat" during the
H:Penal times... Robert Mouland [wireharp@ptdprolog.net]
H:see song file for lyrics and history.
N:Transcribed from the singing in the film version, and also transposed.

D:Anne Lister: Burnt Feathers (1986)Fellside FE059;

X: 477
T:Charlie Mulvihill's Jig
R:jig
C:Charlie Mulvihill?
S:irtrad-l, 8/97, Edward A Beimborn
H:Brendan found the manuscript in a Charlie Mulvihill's attic (as part
H:of his estate, as I recall).  Brendan taught this tune at the 1993
H:Milwaukee summer school, and I transcribed it for the occasion of the
H:Great IRTRAD 1994 Milwaukee Tune Swap.  I put in some, but not all,
H:of the ornaments, which he taught us to do.  More rolls and cuts.

<start>
X: 488
T:An Ri/l Cam
C:Traditional
Z:Gordon Turnbull, Edinburgh
B:CRE1 (107)
N:107.  An Rl Cam [The Crooked Reel]:  The song Follow me down to Carlow is
N:of course sung to this air.  O'Neill has two settings, Follow me down and
N:Follow me down to Carlow (O'N i, 547 and 988). Goodman calls it Miss
N:Murphy (G ii, 156 and G iii, 182).  It is also played as a jig [e.g., as a
N:single jig in CR II, 84].  In Scotland it is called Bonnie Annie.  It is
N:printed in the "Glen Collection of Scottish Dance Music" (i, p;23), from a
N:collection by Dow published c.1775. Aird also printed it (iii, 548). [from
N:Sonny Brogan, accordion][Breandan Breathnach, translation by Paul de Grae]
M:C
L:1/8
N:Posted to the woodenflute mailing list January 2002
K:ADor
(3ABA AG EF G2 | AGAB cded | BA (3B^cd eaaf | (3gfe dB BAdB |
(3ABA AG EF G2 | AGAB cded | BA (3B^cd eaaf | (3gfe dB BA A2 |]
egdg egdc | BG ~G2 Bc d2 | egdg eaaf | (3gfe dB BA A2 |
agef gedB | (3cBA (3BAG EFGB | AGAB cdef | (3gfe dB BA A2 |]
<end>

X: 566
T:Feargal O'Gara's
R:reel
S:cassette [arr. Mason Daring, Daring Music ASCAP. Marblehead MA]
N:Flutes and whistles were:
N:Cormac Breatnach, Mark Roberts and Billy Novich.

% Orchesography.abc
%
% Steve Mansfield March 2001
% steveATlesessionDOTcoDOTuk
%
% A transcription of the music in the 
% Renaissance dance tutor Orchesography, by Thoinot 
% Arbeau, first published in 1589 in Langres.
% 
% This file is to be regarded as a 'playing edition' rather
% than as a scholarly transcription: I would however
% welcome notification of any typing errors to the above email 
% address.
%
% This transcription is based on two editions of the 
% Orchesography, one paper and one virtual. 
% The paper edition is Mary Stewart Evans' translation 
% published by Dover Books 1948 / 1967.
% The Orchesography is also available online in the 
% original French at the wonderful Library of Congress
% 'American Memory' digitisation project - at the time of
% publishing this file the URL for the first page of the 
% Orchesography facsimile is 
% http://memory.loc.gov/cgi-bin/ampage?collId=musdi&fileName=219/musdi219.db&recNum=0&itemLink=r?ammem/musdibib:@OR(@field(AUTHOR+@band(Arbeau,+Thoinot,+1519-1595.+))+@field(OTHER+@band(Arbeau,+Thoinot,+1519-1595.+)))&linkText=0
%
<end>
<start>
X: 1
T:Tabulation for the fife or arigot in the third mode
M:C|
L:1/8
B:Thoinot Arbeau : Orchesographie, 1589
Z:Steve Mansfield February 2001
K:BLoc
GG AB cz zz|GG AB cB cd|cd cB/A/ B4|
BA/B/ c/B/A/G/ A4|AG/A/ B/A/G/F/ G4|GF ED E4|ED EF G4|
CB,/C/ D/C/B,/C/ DE DE|FE/F/ G/F/E/F/ ED/E/ ED/E/|
ED/E/ ED/C/ D4|EDEF G4|GEFG A4|AFGA B4|
BGAB cdcB|cdcB c2 cB/c/|d/c/B/c/ d/c/B/A/ B2 BA/B/|
c/B/A/B/ c/B/A/G/ A2 AG/A/|B/A/G/A/ B/A/G/F/ G4|GAGF E4|
ED/E/ F/E/D/C/ D4|z2 z2 z2 z2|z2 z2 z2 z2|C4 D4|
DC/D/ E/D/C/D/ E4|
ED/E/ F/E/D/E/ F4|FE/F/ G/F/E/F/ G4|GF/G/ A/G/F/G/ A4|
AG/A/ B/A/G/A/ B4|BA/B/ c/B/A/B/ cdcd|cdcd cd cB/c/|
d/c/B/c/ d/c/B/A/ B4|BA/B/ c/B/A/B/ c/B/A/B/ c/B/A/B/|
c/B/A/B/ c/B/A/G/ A4|ABAB ABAF|GABc dcBA|
GABc dcBd|c8|e8|dcde dcde|dcde dcde|

% UmfFaqSessionTunes.abc
%
% The Usenet group uk.music.folk suggest the following as tunes that might well 
%  get you started in a (1-27 English and 28-36 Irish) music session. 
% See the FAQ at http://www.lesession.co.uk/umf for context.
%
% Jack Campin has published a companion file of tunes suitable for a Scottish session at
% http://www.purr.demon.co.uk/jack/Music/ScottishSessionTunes.abc
%
% Different versions of many of these tunes exist, and people who play tunes together 
%  regularly often develop their own subtlely distinct version - YVMV (Your Version May 
%  Vary). Other than obvious transcription errors, which I'd be glad to know of and correct, 
%  please count to ten and Google the phrase 'folk process in action' before emailing 
%  me a complaint that my version is 'wrong'! As a last resort I will claim that all of these 
%  tunes would be instantly recognised in the session at the Bulls Head, Mobberley, Cheshire,
%  on the first and third Tuesday of the month, and you'd be very welcome.
%
% Many of these tunes come from various abc files I've transcribed down the years,
%  hence the varying abc transcription styles: any tunes that I didn't transcribe myself 
%  *should* still have the Z: field in, apologies if your transcription appears here uncredited, 
%  email me and I'll put it right. 
% 
% If the key changes ('K:D') don't work for you try moving them to a line of their own. 
%  If *all* this file is complete gibberish to you, allow me to direct you to 
%  http://www.lesession.co.uk/abc for enlightenment.
%
% Get a beer, get a seat, tune up, and let's go!
% 
% Steve Mansfield, contact(AT)lesession(DOT)co(DOT)uk, 14 October 2006.
% 
<end>

gagf efed | cdcB A2 (3ABc | d2 d2 cecA | d2 d2 cecA | d2 f2 edec | d2 d2 d2 :|
<end>

Be e2 | ec ec | fd fd | e/a/g/f/ e/d/c/B/ | Aa a :|
M:6/8
								2/4/94
********************* INTRODUCTION ***********************************
   This file contains a number of well-known Irish jigs, reels,
hornpipes, and polkas, written out in Chris Walshaw's abc notation. To
print them out, first process the file with the program abc2mtex,
which will convert it to a Music Te
<end>
<start>
X file, and then run that file
through Music Te
<end>
<start>
X. See the abc2mtex documentation for an explanation
of the notation. Both abc2mtex and Music Te
<end>
<start>
X are available for anonymous
ftp on the archive celtic.stanford.edu. 
   Like any folk music, these tunes change with time. There may be
quite different versions of some of them floating around. I have tried
to give settings which are close to what I hear played. A few tunes
are transcribed from particular performances, one or two others are
taken from books--both of these are indicated on the tune notes--but the
majority are set about as I have heard them played. 
   Quite a lot is left to the player. The settings are basic: the only
decorations indicated explicitly are rolls, triplets and quadruplets;
first and second endings are only written out when they are
substantially different. Apart from the fact that most players don't
need to be told when and where to put in a grace note, a lot of gracings
are done differently on different instruments: carefully-written-out
fiddle decorations can be a distraction to someone playing the tune on a
flute. Since the decorations are only indicated generically, not in
detail, the tunes should be playable on any of the usual instruments.
(Well..I have only checked them out on the whistle and pipes.) If some
of the details of the settings turn out to be awkward on a particular
instrument, just adapt the tune to fit--most players automatically
modify a tune slightly in order to make it fit the fingers, or to take
advantage of some particular effect on their instrument. (There are a
couple of obvious cases, where, for instance, the range is beyond the
range of the pipes, whistle, and flute. It is up to the individual to
modify the setting--i.e. to fake it--if they want to play it.) 
   One thing bears noting: I have written the hornpipes out in
straight eighth notes, but they are usually played with alternating
dotted and cut notes: i.e. what I have written as "eighth, eighth,
eighth, eighth" is often played more like "dotted eighth, sixteenth,
dotted eighth, sixteenth." The amount of emphasis is a matter of
style, so some books write out the dotted notes, others don't. I opted
for the easiest path, and wrote them out in straight eighths. 
	Thanks to Dan Beimborn and Seamus Keleher for suggesting
many of these tunes. (Cryptic notations such as Z:Boston just indicate
that the tune is commonly played in sessions there.  But in fact, most of
these tunes will be played in sessions all over.)
   I make apologies in advance for the typos which have surely
escaped my proof-reading. Please let me know about any obvious errors,
or any settings which seem too much at variance with what is played in
your own area. 
   When I knew the composer of a tune, I indicated it, but I only knew
the composers of a couple of the tunes. If any others have known
composers, I would appreciate hearing about it. As far as I know, the
remainder of the tunes are public domain. The copyright below does not
cover the tunes themselves, just the arrangements and the code in this
file. 
	
   Tune 35 is from Bulmer and Sharpley' book; tune 15 from Ceol
Rince na hEireann, tune 49 from Leo Rowsome's tutor, tune 4 from
O'Neill's. The remainder of this file is copyright by John B. Walsh,
January, 1994. It may be freely used, copied and distributed, as long as
this notice is included with the copy. It may not be sold, or used to
make hard copies for sale, without express permission of the author. 
************************* DOUBLE JIGS *********************************
<end>

X:14
T: Gold Ring, The
M:6/8
Z:Boston.  This is one of the "big" jigs for the uilleann pipes.
Z:(Not so bad on a fiddle either, it's just that it goes so well 
Z:on the pipes with all those D crans.) If it's a standard in a session, there 
Z:are probably pipers around. Seamus Ennis used to tell the story of 
Z:its origin: it was originally learned from the fairies.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% SESSION TUNES II %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
		  	Compiled and deranged by John B. Walsh
					
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% INTRODUCTION %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
   This file contains a number of well-known Irish jigs, reels,
hornpipes, and polkas, written out in abc notation. All of them (with
one or two possible exceptions that I slipped in bacause I liked them)
are reasonably common session tunes. The notation is straightforward,
and can be read directly with a little practice, or it can be
converted to standard music notation with Chris Walshaw's program
abc2mtex. The notation is explained in the documentation for the program
abc2mtex, and can be found on the ceolas archive at celtic.stanford.edu.
   There may be quite different versions of some of the tunes floating
around. A few tunes are transcribed from particular performances, but in general I have tried to give settings which are close to what I hear
played in sessions.  
   Quite a lot is left to the player. The settings are basic: the only
decorations indicated explicitly are rolls, triplets and quadruplets;
first and second endings are only written out when they are
substantially different.
    There are notes on the tunes in an accompanying file,
sessionTunesII.txt. I apologize in advance for the many typos which have
surely escaped my proof-reading. Please let me know about any obvious
errors in either the tunes or the notes, or any settings which seem
too much at variance with what is played in your own area. I'd also be
interested in any more lore about the tunes.
   When I knew the composer of a tune, I indicated it, but I only know
the composers of a couple of them. If any others have known composers, I
would appreciate hearing about it. As far as I know, all the the tunes
are in the public domain.
   To print them out, first process this file with the program
abc2mtex, which will convert it to a Music Te
<end>
<start>
X file, and then run that
file through Music Te
<end>
<start>
X. See the abc2mtex documentation to see how to
do this. Both abc2mtex and Music Te
<end>
<start>
X are available for anonymous ftp
on the ceolas archive at celtic.stanford.edu.
   Some technicalities: the tunes are set-up for printing out at eight
bars per line (saves paper) with Music Te
<end>
<start>
X's 17 point music font, with
the music right-justified. The file header.tex, where abc2mtex looks
up the parameters, has entries for the page length, width, margins and
fonts: 
				% page length
				\vsize=9.5in
				% page width
				\hsize=7.7in
				% top margin
				\voffset=-0.25in
				% left margin
				\hoffset=-0.75in
				\musicsize=17\relax
   This works on 8 1/2 x 11 paper, but may not be good for A4, which
is narrower. The output might look better at 4 bars per line with a
larger font, (\musicsize=20) but to make it look nice one has to do
two things: first, replace the backslashes by asterisks at the end of
each 4-bar line (this causes the program to right-justify the lines) and
then fool around with the "E:" field, which governs the note spacing.
Increase the number if the lines are too cramped, (e.g. replace E:7 by
E:10) decrease it if they overflow. The right-justification of lines
looks good if the note spacing is right, but it can look awful if the
note spacing is wrong. To turn it off, just remove all the asterisks
from the end of the lines with a global search-and-replace. 
	Enjoy!
	John Walsh
	walsh@math.ubc.ca
	May 11, 1995
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%  JIGS   %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
<end>

M:C|
   These tunes were originally published in various issues of the
Irish Pipers' Club newsletter, Iris na bPiobairi, the Pipers' Review.
They were published in the hope of providing a few common tunes for
uilleann pipers, so it seems appropriate to reprint them here to give
them a wider exposure. 
						John Walsh
						walsh@math.ubca.ca
	From the article in the Review:
   The manuscript tunes given here are lesson pieces played in
Seattle. Many people from around the country have asked for the
inclusion of some tunes in the Review in order that a common
repertoire can be established. We know well how different regions have
dissimilar bodies of tunes. This is the first step. 
   The [first] two polkas were collected in Newmarket, Co. Cork in
1975 from the playing of local musicians. The reel "The One-Horned
Cow" (The Half-horned Cow) is after the playing of Liam Walsh, a
Waterford piper (see IPC tape #3). The Lodge Road is a set dance tune
after the playing of Sean Maguire, combined with some of the features of
the air in O'Neill's 1001 Gems. Miss Monaghan and the Irish Rover are
after the piping of Leo Rowsome. The double jig When the Cock Crows...
is rather faithful to Seamus Ennis' version, and the Mist on the
Valley is largely from the flute-playing of Charley Higgins, Drumkeerin,
Co. Leitrim. 
   Johnny Mickie's Slide is from the playing of Denis Brooks and is
copied from a manuscript of his. It also goes well when transposed in G.
Denis learned it while living in northwest Cork. 
	
	The final three polkas are from Denis Brooks, who associates them
with a great session that took place at the Top of Croom in West Cork whith
Peter Heelan, Sabra Daly and Seamus Creagh in 1988. They make a nice set.
--------------------------cut here---------------------------------------
You may need the following macros.  Add them to zmacros.tex if they are not
already there.
\def\Zubbzbb#1#2#3#4#5{\Ibu0{#1}{#5}3\qh0{#1}\qh0{#2}\enotes%
\grace\Zlz#3\egrace\notes\qh0{#4}\tqh0{#5}}%
\def\Zlbbzbb#1#2#3#4#5{\Ibl0{#1}{#5}3\qb0{#1}\qb0{#2}\enotes%
\grace\hskip -.5\noteskip\Zuz#3\egrace\notes\qb0{#4}\tqb0{#5}}%
\def\Zlbzbb#1#2#3#4{\Ibl0{#1}{#4}2\qb0{#1}\enotes%
\grace\hskip -.5\noteskip\Zuz#2\egrace\notes\qb0{#3}\tqb0{#4}}%
\def\Zubzbb#1#2#3#4{\Ibu0{#1}{#4}2\qh0{#1}\enotes%
\grace\Zlz#2\egrace\notes\qh0{#3}\tqh0{#4}}%

<end>
